# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: multiprocessing-python
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The `concurrent.futures` module provides a high-level interface for asynchronously executing callables.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The asynchronous execution can be performed with threads, using `ThreadPoolExecutor` or `InterpreterPoolExecutor`, or separate processes, using `ProcessPoolExecutor`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Each implements the same interface, which is defined by the abstract `Executor` class.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] `concurrent.futures.Future` must not be confused with `asyncio.Future`, which is designed for use with `asyncio` tasks and coroutines.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] See the asyncio’s Future documentation for a detailed comparison of the two.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] This module does not work or is not available on WebAssembly.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] See WebAssembly platforms for more information.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] An abstract class that provides methods to execute calls asynchronously.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] It should not be used directly, but through its concrete subclasses.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Schedules the callable, *fn*, to be executed as `fn(*args, **kwargs)` and returns a `Future` object representing the execution of the callable.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The returned iterator raises a `TimeoutError` if `__next__()` is called and the result isn’t available after *timeout* seconds from the original call to `Executor.map()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] If *timeout* is not specified or `None`, there is no limit to the wait time.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] If a *fn* call raises an exception, then that exception will be raised when its value is retrieved from the iterator.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] When using `ProcessPoolExecutor`, this method chops *iterables* into a number of chunks which it submits to the pool as separate tasks.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The (approximate) size of these chunks can be specified by setting *chunksize* to a positive integer.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] For very long iterables, using a large value for *chunksize* can significantly improve performance compared to the default size of 1.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] With `ThreadPoolExecutor` and `InterpreterPoolExecutor`, *chunksize* has no effect.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Changed in version 3.5: Added the *chunksize* parameter.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Changed in version 3.14: Added the *buffersize* parameter.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Signal the executor that it should free any resources that it is using when the currently pending futures are done executing.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Calls to `Executor.submit()` and `Executor.map()` made after shutdown will raise `RuntimeError`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] If *wait* is `True` then this method will not return until all the pending futures are done executing and the resources associated with the executor have been freed.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] If *wait* is `False` then this method will return immediately and the resources associated with the executor will be freed when all pending futures are done executing.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Regardless of the value of *wait*, the entire Python program will not exit until all pending futures are done executing.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] If *cancel_futures* is `True`, this method will cancel all pending futures that the executor has not started running.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Any futures that are completed or running won’t be cancelled, regardless of the value of *cancel_futures*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] If both *cancel_futures* and *wait* are `True`, all futures that the executor has started running will be completed prior to this method returning.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Changed in version 3.9: Added *cancel_futures*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] `ThreadPoolExecutor` is an `Executor` subclass that uses a pool of threads to execute calls asynchronously.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Deadlocks can occur when the callable associated with a `Future` waits on the results of another `Future`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] An `Executor` subclass that uses a pool of at most *max_workers* threads to execute calls asynchronously.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] All threads enqueued to `ThreadPoolExecutor` will be joined before the interpreter can exit.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Note that the exit handler which does this is executed *before* any exit handlers added using `atexit`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] This means exceptions in the main thread must be caught and handled in order to signal threads to exit gracefully.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] For this reason, it is recommended that `ThreadPoolExecutor` not be used for long-running tasks.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Changed in version 3.6: Added the *thread_name_prefix* parameter to allow users to control the `threading.Thread` names for worker threads created by the pool for easier debugging.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Changed in version 3.7: Added the *initializer* and *initargs* arguments.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Changed in version 3.8: Default value of *max_workers* is changed to `min(32, os.cpu_count() + 4)`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] This default value preserves at least 5 workers for I/O bound tasks.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] It utilizes at most 32 CPU cores for CPU bound tasks which release the GIL.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] And it avoids using very large resources implicitly on many-core machines.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] ThreadPoolExecutor now reuses idle worker threads before starting *max_workers* worker threads too.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Changed in version 3.13: Default value of *max_workers* is changed to `min(32, (os.process_cpu_count() or 1) + 4)`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The `InterpreterPoolExecutor` class uses a pool of interpreters to execute calls asynchronously.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] It is a `ThreadPoolExecutor` subclass, which means each worker is running in its own thread.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The difference here is that each worker has its own interpreter, and runs each task using that interpreter.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The biggest benefit to using interpreters instead of only threads is true multi-core parallelism.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Each interpreter has its own Global Interpreter Lock, so code running in one interpreter can run on one CPU core, while code in another interpreter runs unblocked on a different core.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The tradeoff is that writing concurrent code for use with multiple interpreters can take extra effort.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] However, this is because it forces you to be deliberate about how and when interpreters interact, and to be explicit about what data is shared between interpreters.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] This results in several benefits that help balance the extra effort, including true multi-core parallelism, For example, code written this way can make it easier to reason about concurrency.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Another major benefit is that you don’t have to deal with several of the big pain points of using threads, like race conditions.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Each worker’s interpreter is isolated from all the other interpreters. “Isolated” means each interpreter has its own runtime state and operates completely independently.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] For example, if you redirect `sys.stdout` in one interpreter, it will not be automatically redirected to any other interpreter.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] If you import a module in one interpreter, it is not automatically imported in any other.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] You would need to import the module separately in interpreter where you need it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] In fact, each module imported in an interpreter is a completely separate object from the same module in a different interpreter, including `sys`, `builtins`, and even `__main__`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Isolation means a mutable object, or other data, cannot be used by more than one interpreter at the same time.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] That effectively means interpreters cannot actually share such objects or data.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Instead, each interpreter must have its own copy, and you will have to synchronize any changes between the copies manually.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Immutable objects and data, like the builtin singletons, strings, and tuples of immutable objects, don’t have these limitations.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Communicating and synchronizing between interpreters is most effectively done using dedicated tools, like those proposed in **PEP 734**.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] One less efficient alternative is to serialize with `pickle` and then send the bytes over a shared `socket` or `pipe`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] A `ThreadPoolExecutor` subclass that executes calls asynchronously using a pool of at most *max_workers* threads.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Each thread runs tasks in its own interpreter.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The worker interpreters are isolated from each other, which means each has its own runtime state and that they can’t share any mutable objects or other data.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Each interpreter has its own Global Interpreter Lock, which means code run with this executor has true multi-core parallelism.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The optional *initializer* and *initargs* arguments have the same meaning as for `ThreadPoolExecutor`: the initializer is run when each worker is created, though in this case it is run in the worker’s interpreter.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The executor serializes the *initializer* and *initargs* using `pickle` when sending them to the worker’s interpreter.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The executor may replace uncaught exceptions from *initializer* with `ExecutionFailed`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Other caveats from parent `ThreadPoolExecutor` apply here.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] `submit()` and `map()` work like normal, except the worker serializes the callable and arguments using `pickle` when sending them to its interpreter.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The worker likewise serializes the return value when sending it back.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] When a worker’s current task raises an uncaught exception, the worker always tries to preserve the exception as-is.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] If that is successful then it also sets the `__cause__` to a corresponding `ExecutionFailed` instance, which contains a summary of the original exception.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] In the uncommon case that the worker is not able to preserve the original as-is then it directly preserves the corresponding `ExecutionFailed` instance instead.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The `ProcessPoolExecutor` class is an `Executor` subclass that uses a pool of processes to execute calls asynchronously.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] `ProcessPoolExecutor` uses the `multiprocessing` module, which allows it to side-step the Global Interpreter Lock but also means that only picklable objects can be executed and returned.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] The `__main__` module must be importable by worker subprocesses.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] This means that `ProcessPoolExecutor` will not work in the interactive interpreter.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Calling `Executor` or `Future` methods from a callable submitted to a `ProcessPoolExecutor` will result in deadlock.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Note that the restrictions on functions and arguments needing to picklable as per `multiprocessing.Process` apply when using `submit()` and `map()` on a `ProcessPoolExecutor`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] A function defined in a REPL or a lambda should not be expected to work.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] An `Executor` subclass that executes calls asynchronously using a pool of at most *max_workers* processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] If *max_workers* is `None` or not given, it will default to `os.process_cpu_count()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] If *max_workers* is less than or equal to `0`, then a `ValueError` will be raised.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] On Windows, *max_workers* must be less than or equal to `61`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] If it is not then `ValueError` will be raised.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] If *max_workers* is `None`, then the default chosen will be at most `61`, even if more processors are available.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] *mp_context* can be a `multiprocessing` context or `None`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] If *mp_context* is `None` or not given, the default `multiprocessing` context is used.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Bugs have been reported when using the *max_tasks_per_child* feature that can result in the `ProcessPoolExecutor` hanging in some circumstances.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Follow its eventual resolution in gh-115634.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Changed in version 3.3: When one of the worker processes terminates abruptly, a `BrokenProcessPool` error is now raised.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Previously, behaviour was undefined but operations on the executor or its futures would often freeze or deadlock.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Changed in version 3.7: The *mp_context* argument was added to allow users to control the start_method for worker processes created by the pool.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Added the *initializer* and *initargs* arguments.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Changed in version 3.11: The *max_tasks_per_child* argument was added to allow users to control the lifetime of workers in the pool.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Changed in version 3.12: On POSIX systems, if your application has multiple threads and the `multiprocessing` context uses the `"fork"` start method: The `os.fork()` function called internally to spawn workers may raise a `DeprecationWarning`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Pass a *mp_context* configured to use a different start method.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] See the `os.fork()` documentation for further explanation.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Changed in version 3.13: *max_workers* uses `os.process_cpu_count()` by default, instead of `os.cpu_count()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Changed in version 3.14: The default process start method (see Contexts and start methods) changed away from *fork*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] If you require the *fork* start method for `ProcessPoolExecutor` you must explicitly pass `mp_context=multiprocessing.get_context("fork")`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Attempt to terminate all living worker processes immediately by calling `Process.terminate` on each of them.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Internally, it will also call `Executor.shutdown()` to ensure that all other resources associated with the executor are freed.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] After calling this method the caller should no longer submit tasks to the executor.
[src:multiprocessing-python/concurrent-futures] Attempt to kill all living worker processes immediately by calling `Process.kill` on each of them.
