[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] A **global interpreter lock** (**GIL**) is a mechanism used in computer-language interpreters to synchronize the execution of threads so that only one native thread (per process) can execute basic operations (such as memory allocation and reference counting) at a time.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] As a general rule, an interpreter that uses GIL will see only one thread to execute at a time, even if it runs on a multi-core processor, although some implementations provide for CPU intensive code to release the GIL, allowing multiple threads to use multiple cores.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] Some popular interpreters that have a GIL are CPython and Ruby MRI.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] A global interpreter lock (GIL) is a mutual-exclusion lock held by a programming language interpreter thread to avoid sharing code that is not thread-safe with other threads.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] In implementations with a GIL, there is always one GIL for each interpreter process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] Applications running on implementations with a GIL can be designed to use separate processes to achieve full parallelism, as each process has its own interpreter and in turn has its own GIL.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] Otherwise, the GIL can be a significant barrier to parallelism.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] A way to get around a GIL is creating a separate interpreter per thread, which is too expensive with most languages.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] Use of a global interpreter lock in a language effectively limits the amount of parallelism reachable through concurrency of a single interpreter process with multiple threads.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] Due to signaling with a CPU-bound thread, it can cause a significant slowdown, even on single processors.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] More seriously, when the single native thread calls a blocking OS process (such as disk access), the entire process is blocked, even though other application threads may be waiting.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] Some language implementations that implement a global interpreter lock are CPython, the most widely-used implementation of Python, and Ruby MRI, the reference implementation of Ruby (where it is called Global VM Lock).
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] JVM-based equivalents of these languages (Jython and JRuby) do not use global interpreter locks.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] IronPython and IronRuby are implemented on top of Microsoft's Dynamic Language Runtime and also avoid using a GIL.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] An example of an interpreted language without a GIL is Tcl, which is used in the benchmarking tool HammerDB.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] Notice how a lock is acquired and released between each instruction call.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] It uses the Lock object from the threading module.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] In Python 3.13, an experimental "free-threaded" build of CPython was introduced as part of PEP 703 – *Making the Global Interpreter Lock Optional in CPython*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] This build allows developers to compile Python without the Global Interpreter Lock (GIL), enabling true parallel execution of Python bytecode across multiple CPU cores.
[src:multiprocessing-python/global-interpreter-lock] The feature is still experimental but represents a major step toward improved concurrency in future Python releases.
[src:multiprocessing-python/inter-process-communication] In computer science, **interprocess communication** (**IPC**) is the sharing of data between running processes in a computer system, or between multiple such systems.
[src:multiprocessing-python/inter-process-communication] Mechanisms for IPC may be provided by an operating system.
[src:multiprocessing-python/inter-process-communication] Applications which use IPC are often categorized as clients and servers, where the client requests data and the server responds to client requests.
[src:multiprocessing-python/inter-process-communication] Many applications are both clients and servers, as commonly seen in distributed computing.
[src:multiprocessing-python/inter-process-communication] IPC is very important to the design process for microkernels and nanokernels, which reduce the number of functionalities provided by the kernel.
[src:multiprocessing-python/inter-process-communication] Those functionalities are then obtained by communicating with servers via IPC, leading to a large increase in communication when compared to a regular monolithic kernel.
[src:multiprocessing-python/inter-process-communication] IPC interfaces generally encompass variable analytic framework structures.
[src:multiprocessing-python/inter-process-communication] These processes ensure compatibility between the multi-vector protocols upon which IPC models rely.
[src:multiprocessing-python/inter-process-communication] An IPC mechanism is either synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:multiprocessing-python/inter-process-communication] Synchronization primitives may be used to have synchronous behavior with an asynchronous IPC mechanism.
[src:multiprocessing-python/inter-process-communication] Merging data from two processes can often incur significantly higher costs compared to processing the same data on a single thread, potentially by two or more orders of magnitude due to overheads such as inter-process communication and synchronization.
[src:multiprocessing-python/inter-process-communication] Different approaches to IPC have been tailored to different software requirements, such as performance, modularity, and system circumstances such as network bandwidth and latency.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Availability: not Android, not iOS, not WASI.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] This module is not supported on mobile platforms or WebAssembly platforms.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] `multiprocessing` is a package that supports spawning processes using an API similar to the `threading` module.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] The `multiprocessing` package offers both local and remote concurrency, effectively side-stepping the Global Interpreter Lock by using subprocesses instead of threads.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Due to this, the `multiprocessing` module allows the programmer to fully leverage multiple processors on a given machine.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] The `multiprocessing` module also introduces the `Pool` object which offers a convenient means of parallelizing the execution of a function across multiple input values, distributing the input data across processes (data parallelism).
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] The following example demonstrates the common practice of defining such functions in a module so that child processes can successfully import that module.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] The `multiprocessing` module also introduces APIs which do not have analogs in the `threading` module, like the ability to `terminate`, `interrupt` or `kill` a running process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] `concurrent.futures.ProcessPoolExecutor` offers a higher level interface to push tasks to a background process without blocking execution of the calling process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Compared to using the `Pool` interface directly, the `concurrent.futures` API more readily allows the submission of work to the underlying process pool to be separated from waiting for the results.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] In `multiprocessing`, processes are spawned by creating a `Process` object and then calling its `start()` method.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] `Process` follows the API of `threading.Thread`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] For an explanation of why the `if __name__ == '__main__'` part is necessary, see Programming guidelines.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] The arguments to `Process` usually need to be picklable so they can be passed to the child process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] If you tried typing the above example directly into a REPL it could lead to an `AttributeError` in the child process trying to locate the *f* function in the `__main__` module.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Depending on the platform, `multiprocessing` supports three ways to start a process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Changed in version 3.4: *spawn* added on all POSIX platforms, and *forkserver* added for some POSIX platforms.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Child processes no longer inherit all of the parents inheritable handles on Windows.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Changed in version 3.8: On macOS, the *spawn* start method is now the default.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] The *fork* start method should be considered unsafe as it can lead to crashes of the subprocess as macOS system libraries may start threads.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Changed in version 3.14: On POSIX platforms the default start method was changed from *fork* to *forkserver* to retain the performance but avoid common multithreaded process incompatibilities.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] On POSIX using the *spawn* or *forkserver* start methods will also start a *resource tracker* process which tracks the unlinked named system resources (such as named semaphores or `SharedMemory` objects) created by processes of the program.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] When all processes have exited the resource tracker unlinks any remaining tracked object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Usually there should be none, but if a process was killed by a signal there may be some “leaked” resources.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] (Neither leaked semaphores nor shared memory segments will be automatically unlinked until the next reboot.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] To select a start method you use the `set_start_method()` in the `if __name__ == '__main__'` clause of the main module.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] `set_start_method()` should not be used more than once in the program.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Alternatively, you can use `get_context()` to obtain a context object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Context objects have the same API as the multiprocessing module, and allow one to use multiple start methods in the same program.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Note that objects related to one context may not be compatible with processes for a different context.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] In particular, locks created using the *fork* context cannot be passed to processes started using the *spawn* or *forkserver* start methods.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Libraries using `multiprocessing` or `ProcessPoolExecutor` should be designed to allow their users to provide their own multiprocessing context.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Using a specific context of your own within a library can lead to incompatibilities with the rest of the library user’s application.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Always document if your library requires a specific start method.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] The `'spawn'` and `'forkserver'` start methods generally cannot be used with “frozen” executables (i.e., binaries produced by packages like **PyInstaller** and **cx_Freeze**) on POSIX systems.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] The `'fork'` start method may work if code does not use threads.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] `multiprocessing` contains equivalents of all the synchronization primitives from `threading`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Without using the lock output from the different processes is liable to get all mixed up.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] As mentioned above, when doing concurrent programming it is usually best to avoid using shared state as far as possible.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] This is particularly true when using multiple processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] However, if you really do need to use some shared data then `multiprocessing` provides a couple of ways of doing so.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] The `Pool` class represents a pool of worker processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] It has methods which allows tasks to be offloaded to the worker processes in a few different ways.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Note that the methods of a pool should only ever be used by the process which created it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] Functionality within this package requires that the `__main__` module be importable by the children.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] This is covered in Programming guidelines however it is worth pointing out here.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p01] This means that some examples, such as the `multiprocessing.pool.Pool` examples will not work in the interactive interpreter.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The `multiprocessing` package mostly replicates the API of the `threading` module.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Python supports several ways to create and initialize a process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The global start method sets the default mechanism for creating a process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Several multiprocessing functions and methods that may also instantiate certain objects will implicitly set the global start method to the system’s default, if it hasn’t been set already.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The global start method can only be set once.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If you need to change the start method from the system default, you must proactively set the global start method before calling functions or methods, or creating these objects.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Process objects represent activity that is run in a separate process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The `Process` class has equivalents of all the methods of `threading.Thread`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The constructor should always be called with keyword arguments.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] *group* should always be `None`; it exists solely for compatibility with `threading.Thread`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] *target* is the callable object to be invoked by the `run()` method.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] It defaults to `None`, meaning nothing is called.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] *name* is the process name (see `name` for more details).
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] *args* is the argument tuple for the target invocation.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] *kwargs* is a dictionary of keyword arguments for the target invocation.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If provided, the keyword-only *daemon* argument sets the process `daemon` flag to `True` or `False`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If `None` (the default), this flag will be inherited from the creating process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] By default, no arguments are passed to *target*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The *args* argument, which defaults to `()`, can be used to specify a list or tuple of the arguments to pass to *target*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If a subclass overrides the constructor, it must make sure it invokes the base class constructor (`super().__init__()`) before doing anything else to the process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] In general, all arguments to `Process` must be picklable.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This is frequently observed when trying to create a `Process` or use a `concurrent.futures.ProcessPoolExecutor` from a REPL with a locally defined *target* function.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Passing a callable object defined in the current REPL session causes the child process to die via an uncaught `AttributeError` exception when starting as *target* must have been defined within an importable module in order to be loaded during unpickling.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] See The spawn and forkserver start methods.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] While this restriction is not true if using the `"fork"` start method, as of Python `3.14` that is no longer the default on any platform.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Changed in version 3.3: Added the *daemon* parameter.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Method representing the process’s activity.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] You may override this method in a subclass.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The standard `run()` method invokes the callable object passed to the object’s constructor as the target argument, if any, with sequential and keyword arguments taken from the *args* and *kwargs* arguments, respectively.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Using a list or tuple as the *args* argument passed to `Process` achieves the same effect.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This must be called at most once per process object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] It arranges for the object’s `run()` method to be invoked in a separate process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If the optional argument *timeout* is `None` (the default), the method blocks until the process whose `join()` method is called terminates.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *timeout* is a positive number, it blocks at most *timeout* seconds.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that the method returns `None` if its process terminates or if the method times out.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Check the process’s `exitcode` to determine if it terminated.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] A process cannot join itself because this would cause a deadlock.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] It is an error to attempt to join a process before it has been started.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The name is a string used for identification purposes only.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Multiple processes may be given the same name.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The initial name is set by the constructor.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If no explicit name is provided to the constructor, a name of the form ‘Process-N1:N2:…:Nk’ is constructed, where each Nk is the N-th child of its parent.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Roughly, a process object is alive from the moment the `start()` method returns until the child process terminates.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The process’s daemon flag, a Boolean value.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This must be set before `start()` is called.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The initial value is inherited from the creating process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] When a process exits, it attempts to terminate all of its daemonic child processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that a daemonic process is not allowed to create child processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Otherwise a daemonic process would leave its children orphaned if it gets terminated when its parent process exits.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Additionally, these are **not** Unix daemons or services, they are normal processes that will be terminated (and not joined) if non-daemonic processes have exited.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Before the process is spawned, this will be `None`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This will be `None` if the process has not yet terminated.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If the child’s `run()` method returned normally, the exit code will be 0.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If it terminated via `sys.exit()` with an integer argument *N*, the exit code will be *N*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If the child terminated due to an exception not caught within `run()`, the exit code will be 1.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If it was terminated by signal *N*, the exit code will be the negative value *-N*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The process’s authentication key (a byte string).
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] When `multiprocessing` is initialized the main process is assigned a random string using `os.urandom()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] When a `Process` object is created, it will inherit the authentication key of its parent process, although this may be changed by setting `authkey` to another byte string.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] A numeric handle of a system object which will become “ready” when the process ends.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] You can use this value if you want to wait on several events at once using `multiprocessing.connection.wait()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] On Windows, this is an OS handle usable with the `WaitForSingleObject` and `WaitForMultipleObjects` family of API calls.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] On POSIX, this is a file descriptor usable with primitives from the `select` module.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Works on POSIX using the `SIGINT` signal.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] By default, this terminates the child process by raising `KeyboardInterrupt`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This behavior can be altered by setting the respective signal handler in the child process `signal.signal()` for `SIGINT`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note: if the child process catches and discards `KeyboardInterrupt`, the process will not be terminated.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note: the default behavior will also set `exitcode` to `1` as if an uncaught exception was raised in the child process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] To have a different `exitcode` you may simply catch `KeyboardInterrupt` and call `exit(your_code)`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] On POSIX this is done using the `SIGTERM` signal; on Windows `TerminateProcess()` is used.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that exit handlers and finally clauses, etc., will not be executed.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that descendant processes of the process will *not* be terminated – they will simply become orphaned.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If this method is used when the associated process is using a pipe or queue then the pipe or queue is liable to become corrupted and may become unusable by other process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Similarly, if the process has acquired a lock or semaphore etc. then terminating it is liable to cause other processes to deadlock.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Same as `terminate()` but using the `SIGKILL` signal on POSIX.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Close the `Process` object, releasing all resources associated with it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] `ValueError` is raised if the underlying process is still running.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Once `close()` returns successfully, most other methods and attributes of the `Process` object will raise `ValueError`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that the `start()`, `join()`, `is_alive()`, `terminate()` and `exitcode` methods should only be called by the process that created the process object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The base class of all `multiprocessing` exceptions.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Exception raised by `Connection.recv_bytes_into()` when the supplied buffer object is too small for the message read.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If `e` is an instance of `BufferTooShort` then `e.args[0]` will give the message as a byte string.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Raised when there is an authentication error.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Raised by methods with a timeout when the timeout expires.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] When using multiple processes, one generally uses message passing for communication between processes and avoids having to use any synchronization primitives like locks.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] For passing messages one can use `Pipe()` (for a connection between two processes) or a queue (which allows multiple producers and consumers).
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The `Queue`, `SimpleQueue` and `JoinableQueue` types are multi-producer, multi-consumer FIFO queues modelled on the `queue.Queue` class in the standard library.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] They differ in that `Queue` lacks the `task_done()` and `join()` methods introduced into Python 2.5’s `queue.Queue` class.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If you use `JoinableQueue` then you **must** call `JoinableQueue.task_done()` for each task removed from the queue or else the semaphore used to count the number of unfinished tasks may eventually overflow, raising an exception.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] One difference from other Python queue implementations, is that `multiprocessing` queues serializes all objects that are put into them using `pickle`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The object returned by the get method is a re-created object that does not share memory with the original object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that one can also create a shared queue by using a manager object – see Managers.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] `multiprocessing` uses the usual `queue.Empty` and `queue.Full` exceptions to signal a timeout.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] They are not available in the `multiprocessing` namespace so you need to import them from `queue`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] When an object is put on a queue, the object is pickled and a background thread later flushes the pickled data to an underlying pipe.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This has some consequences which are a little surprising, but should not cause any practical difficulties – if they really bother you then you can instead use a queue created with a manager.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If multiple processes are enqueuing objects, it is possible for the objects to be received at the other end out-of-order.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] However, objects enqueued by the same process will always be in the expected order with respect to each other.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If a process is killed using `Process.terminate()` or `os.kill()` while it is trying to use a `Queue`, then the data in the queue is likely to become corrupted.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This may cause any other process to get an exception when it tries to use the queue later on.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] As mentioned above, if a child process has put items on a queue (and it has not used `JoinableQueue.cancel_join_thread`), then that process will not terminate until all buffered items have been flushed to the pipe.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This means that if you try joining that process you may get a deadlock unless you are sure that all items which have been put on the queue have been consumed.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Similarly, if the child process is non-daemonic then the parent process may hang on exit when it tries to join all its non-daemonic children.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that a queue created using a manager does not have this issue.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] For an example of the usage of queues for interprocess communication see Examples.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Returns a pair `(conn1, conn2)` of `Connection` objects representing the ends of a pipe.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *duplex* is `True` (the default) then the pipe is bidirectional.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *duplex* is `False` then the pipe is unidirectional: `conn1` can only be used for receiving messages and `conn2` can only be used for sending messages.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The `send()` method serializes the object using `pickle` and the `recv()` re-creates the object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Returns a process shared queue implemented using a pipe and a few locks/semaphores.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] When a process first puts an item on the queue a feeder thread is started which transfers objects from a buffer into the pipe.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Instantiating this class may set the global start method.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] See Global start method for more details.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The usual `queue.Empty` and `queue.Full` exceptions from the standard library’s `queue` module are raised to signal timeouts.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] `Queue` implements all the methods of `queue.Queue` except for `task_done()`, `join()`, and `shutdown()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return the approximate size of the queue.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Because of multithreading/multiprocessing semantics, this number is not reliable.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that this may raise `NotImplementedError` on platforms like macOS where `sem_getvalue()` is not implemented.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return `True` if the queue is empty, `False` otherwise.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Because of multithreading/multiprocessing semantics, this is not reliable.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] May raise an `OSError` on closed queues.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return `True` if the queue is full, `False` otherwise.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If the optional argument *block* is `True` (the default) and *timeout* is `None` (the default), block if necessary until a free slot is available.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *timeout* is a positive number, it blocks at most *timeout* seconds and raises the `queue.Full` exception if no free slot was available within that time.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Otherwise (*block* is `False`), put an item on the queue if a free slot is immediately available, else raise the `queue.Full` exception (*timeout* is ignored in that case).
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Changed in version 3.8: If the queue is closed, `ValueError` is raised instead of `AssertionError`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Remove and return an item from the queue.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If optional args *block* is `True` (the default) and *timeout* is `None` (the default), block if necessary until an item is available.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *timeout* is a positive number, it blocks at most *timeout* seconds and raises the `queue.Empty` exception if no item was available within that time.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Otherwise (block is `False`), return an item if one is immediately available, else raise the `queue.Empty` exception (*timeout* is ignored in that case).
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Changed in version 3.8: If the queue is closed, `ValueError` is raised instead of `OSError`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] `multiprocessing.Queue` has a few additional methods not found in `queue.Queue`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Close the queue: release internal resources.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] A queue must not be used anymore after it is closed.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] For example, `get()`, `put()` and `empty()` methods must no longer be called.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The background thread will quit once it has flushed all buffered data to the pipe.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This is called automatically when the queue is garbage collected.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This can only be used after `close()` has been called.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] It blocks until the background thread exits, ensuring that all data in the buffer has been flushed to the pipe.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] By default if a process is not the creator of the queue then on exit it will attempt to join the queue’s background thread.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The process can call `cancel_join_thread()` to make `join_thread()` do nothing.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] In particular, this prevents the background thread from being joined automatically when the process exits – see `join_thread()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] A better name for this method might be `allow_exit_without_flush()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] It is likely to cause enqueued data to be lost, and you almost certainly will not need to use it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] It is really only there if you need the current process to exit immediately without waiting to flush enqueued data to the underlying pipe, and you don’t care about lost data.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This class’s functionality requires a functioning shared semaphore implementation on the host operating system.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Without one, the functionality in this class will be disabled, and attempts to instantiate a `Queue` will result in an `ImportError`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] See bpo-3770 for additional information.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The same holds true for any of the specialized queue types listed below.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] It is a simplified `Queue` type, very close to a locked `Pipe`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Always raises an `OSError` if the SimpleQueue is closed.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] `JoinableQueue`, a `Queue` subclass, is a queue which additionally has `task_done()` and `join()` methods.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Indicate that a formerly enqueued task is complete.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] For each `get()` used to fetch a task, a subsequent call to `task_done()` tells the queue that the processing on the task is complete.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If a `join()` is currently blocking, it will resume when all items have been processed (meaning that a `task_done()` call was received for every item that had been `put()` into the queue).
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Raises a `ValueError` if called more times than there were items placed in the queue.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Block until all items in the queue have been gotten and processed.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The count of unfinished tasks goes up whenever an item is added to the queue.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The count goes down whenever a consumer calls `task_done()` to indicate that the item was retrieved and all work on it is complete.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] When the count of unfinished tasks drops to zero, `join()` unblocks.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return list of all live children of the current process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Calling this has the side effect of “joining” any processes which have already finished.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return the number of CPUs in the system.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This number is not equivalent to the number of CPUs the current process can use.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The number of usable CPUs can be obtained with `os.process_cpu_count()` (or `len(os.sched_getaffinity(0))`).
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] When the number of CPUs cannot be determined a `NotImplementedError` is raised.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Changed in version 3.13: The return value can also be overridden using the `-X cpu_count` flag or `PYTHON_CPU_COUNT` as this is merely a wrapper around the `os` cpu count APIs.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return the `Process` object corresponding to the current process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] An analogue of `threading.current_thread()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return the `Process` object corresponding to the parent process of the `current_process()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] For the main process, `parent_process` will be `None`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Add support for when a program which uses `multiprocessing` has been frozen to produce an executable.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] One needs to call this function straight after the `if __name__ == '__main__'` line of the main module.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If the `freeze_support()` line is omitted then trying to run the frozen executable will raise `RuntimeError`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Calling `freeze_support()` has no effect when the start method is not *spawn*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] In addition, if the module is being run normally by the Python interpreter (the program has not been frozen), then `freeze_support()` has no effect.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Returns a list of the supported start methods, the first of which is the default.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The possible start methods are `'fork'`, `'spawn'` and `'forkserver'`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return a context object which has the same attributes as the `multiprocessing` module.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *method* is `None` then the default context is returned.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that if the global start method has not been set, this will set it to the system default See Global start method for more details.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Otherwise *method* should be `'fork'`, `'spawn'`, `'forkserver'`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] `ValueError` is raised if the specified start method is not available.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return the name of start method used for starting processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If the global start method is not set and *allow_none* is `False`, the global start method is set to the default, and its name is returned.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The return value can be `'fork'`, `'spawn'`, `'forkserver'` or `None`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The *fork* start method should be considered unsafe as it can lead to crashes of the subprocess.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Set the path of the Python interpreter to use when starting a child process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Changed in version 3.4: Now supported on POSIX when the `'spawn'` start method is used.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Changed in version 3.11: Accepts a path-like object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Set a list of module names for the forkserver main process to attempt to import so that their already imported state is inherited by forked processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Any `ImportError` when doing so is silently ignored.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This can be used as a performance enhancement to avoid repeated work in every process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] For this to work, it must be called before the forkserver process has been launched (before creating a `Pool` or starting a `Process`).
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Only meaningful when using the `'forkserver'` start method.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Set the method which should be used to start child processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The *method* argument can be `'fork'`, `'spawn'` or `'forkserver'`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Raises `RuntimeError` if the start method has already been set and *force* is not `True`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *method* is `None` and *force* is `True` then the start method is set to `None`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *method* is `None` and *force* is `False` then the context is set to the default context.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that this should be called at most once, and it should be protected inside the `if __name__ == '__main__'` clause of the main module.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] `multiprocessing` contains no analogues of `threading.active_count()`, `threading.enumerate()`, `threading.settrace()`, `threading.setprofile()`, `threading.Timer`, or `threading.local`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Connection objects allow the sending and receiving of picklable objects or strings.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] They can be thought of as message oriented connected sockets.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Connection objects are usually created using `Pipe` – see also Listeners and Clients.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Send an object to the other end of the connection which should be read using `recv()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Very large pickles (approximately 32 MiB+, though it depends on the OS) may raise a `ValueError` exception.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return an object sent from the other end of the connection using `send()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Blocks until there is something to receive.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Raises `EOFError` if there is nothing left to receive and the other end was closed.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return the file descriptor or handle used by the connection.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This is called automatically when the connection is garbage collected.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return whether there is any data available to be read.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *timeout* is not specified then it will return immediately.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *timeout* is a number then this specifies the maximum time in seconds to block.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *timeout* is `None` then an infinite timeout is used.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that multiple connection objects may be polled at once by using `multiprocessing.connection.wait()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Send byte data from a bytes-like object as a complete message.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *offset* is given then data is read from that position in *buf*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *size* is given then that many bytes will be read from *buf*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return a complete message of byte data sent from the other end of the connection as a string.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Raises `EOFError` if there is nothing left to receive and the other end has closed.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *maxlength* is specified and the message is longer than *maxlength* then `OSError` is raised and the connection will no longer be readable.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Changed in version 3.3: This function used to raise `IOError`, which is now an alias of `OSError`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Read into *buf* a complete message of byte data sent from the other end of the connection and return the number of bytes in the message.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If the buffer is too short then a `BufferTooShort` exception is raised and the complete message is available as `e.args[0]` where `e` is the exception instance.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Changed in version 3.3: Connection objects themselves can now be transferred between processes using `Connection.send()` and `Connection.recv()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Connection objects also now support the context management protocol – see Context Manager Types.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The `Connection.recv()` method automatically unpickles the data it receives, which can be a security risk unless you can trust the process which sent the message.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Therefore, unless the connection object was produced using `Pipe()` you should only use the `recv()` and `send()` methods after performing some sort of authentication.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If a process is killed while it is trying to read or write to a pipe then the data in the pipe is likely to become corrupted, because it may become impossible to be sure where the message boundaries lie.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Generally synchronization primitives are not as necessary in a multiprocess program as they are in a multithreaded program.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] See the documentation for `threading` module.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that one can also create synchronization primitives by using a manager object – see Managers.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] A barrier object: a clone of `threading.Barrier`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] A bounded semaphore object: a close analog of `threading.BoundedSemaphore`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] A solitary difference from its close analog exists: its `acquire` method’s first argument is named *block*, as is consistent with `Lock.acquire()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return a boolean indicating whether this object is locked right now.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] On macOS, this is indistinguishable from `Semaphore` because `sem_getvalue()` is not implemented on that platform.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] A condition variable: an alias for `threading.Condition`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *lock* is specified then it should be a `Lock` or `RLock` object from `multiprocessing`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Changed in version 3.3: The `wait_for()` method was added.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] A non-recursive lock object: a close analog of `threading.Lock`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Once a process or thread has acquired a lock, subsequent attempts to acquire it from any process or thread will block until it is released; any process or thread may release it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The concepts and behaviors of `threading.Lock` as it applies to threads are replicated here in `multiprocessing.Lock` as it applies to either processes or threads, except as noted.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that `Lock` is actually a factory function which returns an instance of `multiprocessing.synchronize.Lock` initialized with a default context.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] `Lock` supports the context manager protocol and thus may be used in `with` statements.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Acquire a lock, blocking or non-blocking.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] With the *block* argument set to `True` (the default), the method call will block until the lock is in an unlocked state, then set it to locked and return `True`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that the name of this first argument differs from that in `threading.Lock.acquire()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] With the *block* argument set to `False`, the method call does not block.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If the lock is currently in a locked state, return `False`; otherwise set the lock to a locked state and return `True`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] When invoked with a positive, floating-point value for *timeout*, block for at most the number of seconds specified by *timeout* as long as the lock can not be acquired.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Invocations with a negative value for *timeout* are equivalent to a *timeout* of zero.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Invocations with a *timeout* value of `None` (the default) set the timeout period to infinite.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that the treatment of negative or `None` values for *timeout* differs from the implemented behavior in `threading.Lock.acquire()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The *timeout* argument has no practical implications if the *block* argument is set to `False` and is thus ignored.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Returns `True` if the lock has been acquired or `False` if the timeout period has elapsed.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] This can be called from any process or thread, not only the process or thread which originally acquired the lock.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Behavior is the same as in `threading.Lock.release()` except that when invoked on an unlocked lock, a `ValueError` is raised.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] A recursive lock object: a close analog of `threading.RLock`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] A recursive lock must be released by the process or thread that acquired it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Once a process or thread has acquired a recursive lock, the same process or thread may acquire it again without blocking; that process or thread must release it once for each time it has been acquired.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that `RLock` is actually a factory function which returns an instance of `multiprocessing.synchronize.RLock` initialized with a default context.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] `RLock` supports the context manager protocol and thus may be used in `with` statements.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] When invoked with the *block* argument set to `True`, block until the lock is in an unlocked state (not owned by any process or thread) unless the lock is already owned by the current process or thread.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The current process or thread then takes ownership of the lock (if it does not already have ownership) and the recursion level inside the lock increments by one, resulting in a return value of `True`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that there are several differences in this first argument’s behavior compared to the implementation of `threading.RLock.acquire()`, starting with the name of the argument itself.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] When invoked with the *block* argument set to `False`, do not block.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If the lock has already been acquired (and thus is owned) by another process or thread, the current process or thread does not take ownership and the recursion level within the lock is not changed, resulting in a return value of `False`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If the lock is in an unlocked state, the current process or thread takes ownership and the recursion level is incremented, resulting in a return value of `True`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Use and behaviors of the *timeout* argument are the same as in `Lock.acquire()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that some of these behaviors of *timeout* differ from the implemented behaviors in `threading.RLock.acquire()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Release a lock, decrementing the recursion level.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If after the decrement the recursion level is zero, reset the lock to unlocked (not owned by any process or thread) and if any other processes or threads are blocked waiting for the lock to become unlocked, allow exactly one of them to proceed.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If after the decrement the recursion level is still nonzero, the lock remains locked and owned by the calling process or thread.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Only call this method when the calling process or thread owns the lock.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] An `AssertionError` is raised if this method is called by a process or thread other than the owner or if the lock is in an unlocked (unowned) state.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that the type of exception raised in this situation differs from the implemented behavior in `threading.RLock.release()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] A semaphore object: a close analog of `threading.Semaphore`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] On macOS, `sem_timedwait` is unsupported, so calling `acquire()` with a timeout will emulate that function’s behavior using a sleeping loop.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Some of this package’s functionality requires a functioning shared semaphore implementation on the host operating system.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Without one, the `multiprocessing.synchronize` module will be disabled, and attempts to import it will result in an `ImportError`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] It is possible to create shared objects using shared memory which can be inherited by child processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return a `ctypes` object allocated from shared memory.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] By default the return value is actually a synchronized wrapper for the object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] The object itself can be accessed via the *value* attribute of a `Value`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *lock* is `True` (the default) then a new recursive lock object is created to synchronize access to the value.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *lock* is a `Lock` or `RLock` object then that will be used to synchronize access to the value.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] If *lock* is `False` then access to the returned object will not be automatically protected by a lock, so it will not necessarily be “process-safe”.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Operations like `+=` which involve a read and write are not atomic.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Note that *lock* is a keyword-only argument.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] Return a ctypes array allocated from shared memory.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p02] By default the return value is actually a synchronized wrapper for the array.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If *lock* is `True` (the default) then a new lock object is created to synchronize access to the value.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Note that *lock* is a keyword only argument.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Note that an array of `ctypes.c_char` has *value* and *raw* attributes which can both be used to store and retrieve byte strings.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] While *raw* allows interaction with a `bytes` object the full size of the array, reading *value* will terminate after a null byte, like most programming languages handle strings.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The `multiprocessing.sharedctypes` module provides functions for allocating `ctypes` objects from shared memory which can be inherited by child processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Although it is possible to store a pointer in shared memory remember that this will refer to a location in the address space of a specific process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] However, the pointer is quite likely to be invalid in the context of a second process and trying to dereference the pointer from the second process may cause a crash.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Note that setting and getting an element is potentially non-atomic – use `Array()` instead to make sure that access is automatically synchronized using a lock.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Return a ctypes object allocated from shared memory.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Note that setting and getting the value is potentially non-atomic – use `Value()` instead to make sure that access is automatically synchronized using a lock.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Note that an array of `ctypes.c_char` has `value` and `raw` attributes which allow one to use it to store and retrieve strings – see documentation for `ctypes`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The same as `RawArray()` except that depending on the value of *lock* a process-safe synchronization wrapper may be returned instead of a raw ctypes array.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Note that *lock* and *ctx* are keyword-only parameters.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The same as `RawValue()` except that depending on the value of *lock* a process-safe synchronization wrapper may be returned instead of a raw ctypes object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Return a ctypes object allocated from shared memory which is a copy of the ctypes object *obj*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Return a process-safe wrapper object for a ctypes object which uses *lock* to synchronize access.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If *lock* is `None` (the default) then a `multiprocessing.RLock` object is created automatically.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A synchronized wrapper will have two methods in addition to those of the object it wraps: `get_obj()` returns the wrapped object and `get_lock()` returns the lock object used for synchronization.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Note that accessing the ctypes object through the wrapper can be a lot slower than accessing the raw ctypes object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Changed in version 3.5: Synchronized objects support the context manager protocol.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The table below compares the syntax for creating shared ctypes objects from shared memory with the normal ctypes syntax.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Managers provide a way to create data which can be shared between different processes, including sharing over a network between processes running on different machines.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A manager object controls a server process which manages *shared objects*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Other processes can access the shared objects by using proxies.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Returns a started `SyncManager` object which can be used for sharing objects between processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The returned manager object corresponds to a spawned child process and has methods which will create shared objects and return corresponding proxies.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Manager processes will be shutdown as soon as they are garbage collected or their parent process exits.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Once created one should call `start()` or `get_server().serve_forever()` to ensure that the manager object refers to a started manager process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Changed in version 3.11: Added the *shutdown_timeout* parameter.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Start a subprocess to start the manager.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If *initializer* is not `None` then the subprocess will call `initializer(*initargs)` when it starts.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Returns a `Server` object which represents the actual server under the control of the Manager.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] `Server` additionally has an `address` attribute.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] This is only available if `start()` has been used to start the server process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A classmethod which can be used for registering a type or callable with the manager class.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Changed in version 3.3: Manager objects support the context management protocol – see Context Manager Types.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] `__enter__()` starts the server process (if it has not already started) and then returns the manager object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] In previous versions `__enter__()` did not start the manager’s server process if it was not already started.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A subclass of `BaseManager` which can be used for the synchronization of processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Objects of this type are returned by `multiprocessing.Manager()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Its methods create and return Proxy Objects for a number of commonly used data types to be synchronized across processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] This notably includes shared lists and dictionaries.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Create a shared `threading.Barrier` object and return a proxy for it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Create a shared `threading.BoundedSemaphore` object and return a proxy for it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Create a shared `threading.Condition` object and return a proxy for it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If *lock* is supplied then it should be a proxy for a `threading.Lock` or `threading.RLock` object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Create a shared `threading.Event` object and return a proxy for it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Create a shared `threading.Lock` object and return a proxy for it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Create a shared `Namespace` object and return a proxy for it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Create a shared `queue.Queue` object and return a proxy for it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Create a shared `threading.RLock` object and return a proxy for it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Create a shared `threading.Semaphore` object and return a proxy for it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Create an array and return a proxy for it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Create an object with a writable `value` attribute and return a proxy for it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Create a shared `dict` object and return a proxy for it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Create a shared `list` object and return a proxy for it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Create a shared `set` object and return a proxy for it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Added in version 3.14: `set` support was added.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Changed in version 3.6: Shared objects are capable of being nested.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] For example, a shared container object such as a shared list can contain other shared objects which will all be managed and synchronized by the `SyncManager`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A type that can register with `SyncManager`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A namespace object has no public methods, but does have writable attributes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Its representation shows the values of its attributes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] To create one’s own manager, one creates a subclass of `BaseManager` and uses the `register()` classmethod to register new types or callables with the manager class.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] It is possible to run a manager server on one machine and have clients use it from other machines (assuming that the firewalls involved allow it).
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A proxy is an object which *refers* to a shared object which lives (presumably) in a different process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The shared object is said to be the *referent* of the proxy.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Multiple proxy objects may have the same referent.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A proxy object has methods which invoke corresponding methods of its referent (although not every method of the referent will necessarily be available through the proxy).
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Notice that applying `str()` to a proxy will return the representation of the referent, whereas applying `repr()` will return the representation of the proxy.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] An important feature of proxy objects is that they are picklable so they can be passed between processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] As such, a referent can contain Proxy Objects.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If standard (non-proxy) `list` or `dict` objects are contained in a referent, modifications to those mutable values will not be propagated through the manager because the proxy has no way of knowing when the values contained within are modified.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] This approach is perhaps less convenient than employing nested Proxy Objects for most use cases but also demonstrates a level of control over the synchronization.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The proxy types in `multiprocessing` do nothing to support comparisons by value.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] One should just use a copy of the referent instead when making comparisons.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Proxy objects are instances of subclasses of `BaseProxy`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Call and return the result of a method of the proxy’s referent.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The returned value will be a copy of the result of the call or a proxy to a new shared object – see documentation for the *method_to_typeid* argument of `BaseManager.register()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If an exception is raised by the call, then is re-raised by `_callmethod()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If some other exception is raised in the manager’s process then this is converted into a `RemoteError` exception and is raised by `_callmethod()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Note in particular that an exception will be raised if *methodname* has not been *exposed*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If the referent is unpicklable then this will raise an exception.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Return a representation of the proxy object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Return the representation of the referent.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A proxy object uses a weakref callback so that when it gets garbage collected it deregisters itself from the manager which owns its referent.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A shared object gets deleted from the manager process when there are no longer any proxies referring to it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] One can create a pool of processes which will carry out tasks submitted to it with the `Pool` class.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A process pool object which controls a pool of worker processes to which jobs can be submitted.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] It supports asynchronous results with timeouts and callbacks and has a parallel map implementation.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If *initializer* is not `None` then each worker process will call `initializer(*initargs)` when it starts.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Note that the methods of the pool object should only be called by the process which created the pool.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] `multiprocessing.pool` objects have internal resources that need to be properly managed (like any other resource) by using the pool as a context manager or by calling `close()` and `terminate()` manually.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Failure to do this can lead to the process hanging on finalization.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Note that it is **not correct** to rely on the garbage collector to destroy the pool as CPython does not assure that the finalizer of the pool will be called (see `object.__del__()` for more information).
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Changed in version 3.2: Added the *maxtasksperchild* parameter.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Changed in version 3.4: Added the *context* parameter.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Changed in version 3.13: *processes* uses `os.process_cpu_count()` by default, instead of `os.cpu_count()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Worker processes within a `Pool` typically live for the complete duration of the Pool’s work queue.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A frequent pattern found in other systems (such as Apache, mod_wsgi, etc) to free resources held by workers is to allow a worker within a pool to complete only a set amount of work before exiting, being cleaned up and a new process spawned to replace the old one.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The *maxtasksperchild* argument to the `Pool` exposes this ability to the end user.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Call *func* with arguments *args* and keyword arguments *kwds*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Given this blocks, `apply_async()` is better suited for performing work in parallel.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Additionally, *func* is only executed in one of the workers of the pool.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A variant of the `apply()` method which returns a `AsyncResult` object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If *callback* is specified then it should be a callable which accepts a single argument.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] When the result becomes ready *callback* is applied to it, that is unless the call failed, in which case the *error_callback* is applied instead.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If *error_callback* is specified then it should be a callable which accepts a single argument.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If the target function fails, then the *error_callback* is called with the exception instance.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Callbacks should complete immediately since otherwise the thread which handles the results will get blocked.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A parallel equivalent of the `map()` built-in function (it supports only one *iterable* argument though, for multiple iterables see `starmap()`).
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] This method chops the iterable into a number of chunks which it submits to the process pool as separate tasks.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Note that it may cause high memory usage for very long iterables.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Consider using `imap()` or `imap_unordered()` with explicit *chunksize* option for better efficiency.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A variant of the `map()` method which returns a `AsyncResult` object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The *chunksize* argument is the same as the one used by the `map()` method.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] For very long iterables using a large value for *chunksize* can make the job complete **much** faster than using the default value of `1`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Also if *chunksize* is `1` then the `next()` method of the iterator returned by the `imap()` method has an optional *timeout* parameter: `next(timeout)` will raise `multiprocessing.TimeoutError` if the result cannot be returned within *timeout* seconds.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The same as `imap()` except that the ordering of the results from the returned iterator should be considered arbitrary.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Like `map()` except that the elements of the *iterable* are expected to be iterables that are unpacked as arguments.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A combination of `starmap()` and `map_async()` that iterates over *iterable* of iterables and calls *func* with the iterables unpacked.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Prevents any more tasks from being submitted to the pool.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Once all the tasks have been completed the worker processes will exit.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Stops the worker processes immediately without completing outstanding work.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] When the pool object is garbage collected `terminate()` will be called immediately.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] One must call `close()` or `terminate()` before using `join()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Changed in version 3.3: Pool objects now support the context management protocol – see Context Manager Types.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The class of the result returned by `Pool.apply_async()` and `Pool.map_async()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If *timeout* is not `None` and the result does not arrive within *timeout* seconds then `multiprocessing.TimeoutError` is raised.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If the remote call raised an exception then that exception will be reraised by `get()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Wait until the result is available or until *timeout* seconds pass.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Return whether the call completed without raising an exception.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Will raise `ValueError` if the result is not ready.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Changed in version 3.7: If the result is not ready, `ValueError` is raised instead of `AssertionError`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Usually message passing between processes is done using queues or by using `Connection` objects returned by `Pipe()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] However, the `multiprocessing.connection` module allows some extra flexibility.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] It basically gives a high level message oriented API for dealing with sockets or Windows named pipes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] It also has support for *digest authentication* using the `hmac` module, and for polling multiple connections at the same time.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Send a randomly generated message to the other end of the connection and wait for a reply.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If the reply matches the digest of the message using *authkey* as the key then a welcome message is sent to the other end of the connection.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Otherwise `AuthenticationError` is raised.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Receive a message, calculate the digest of the message using *authkey* as the key, and then send the digest back.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If a welcome message is not received, then `AuthenticationError` is raised.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Attempt to set up a connection to the listener which is using address *address*, returning a `Connection`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The type of the connection is determined by *family* argument, but this can generally be omitted since it can usually be inferred from the format of *address*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If *authkey* is given and not `None`, it should be a byte string and will be used as the secret key for an HMAC-based authentication challenge.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] No authentication is done if *authkey* is `None`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] `AuthenticationError` is raised if authentication fails.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A wrapper for a bound socket or Windows named pipe which is ‘listening’ for connections.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If an address of ‘0.0.0.0’ is used, the address will not be a connectable end point on Windows.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If you require a connectable end-point, you should use ‘127.0.0.1’.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If the listener object uses a socket then *backlog* (1 by default) is passed to the `listen()` method of the socket once it has been bound.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Accept a connection on the bound socket or named pipe of the listener object and return a `Connection` object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If authentication is attempted and fails, then `AuthenticationError` is raised.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Close the bound socket or named pipe of the listener object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] This is called automatically when the listener is garbage collected.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] However it is advisable to call it explicitly.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The address which is being used by the Listener object.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The address from which the last accepted connection came.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If this is unavailable then it is `None`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Changed in version 3.3: Listener objects now support the context management protocol – see Context Manager Types.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Wait till an object in *object_list* is ready.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Returns the list of those objects in *object_list* which are ready.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If *timeout* is a float then the call blocks for at most that many seconds.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If *timeout* is `None` then it will block for an unlimited period.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A negative timeout is equivalent to a zero timeout.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A connection or socket object is ready when there is data available to be read from it, or the other end has been closed.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] The following server code creates a listener which uses `'secret password'` as an authentication key.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Note that any string beginning with two backslashes is assumed by default to be an `'AF_PIPE'` address rather than an `'AF_UNIX'` address.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] When one uses `Connection.recv`, the data received is automatically unpickled.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Unfortunately unpickling data from an untrusted source is a security risk.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Therefore `Listener` and `Client()` use the `hmac` module to provide digest authentication.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] An authentication key is a byte string which can be thought of as a password: once a connection is established both ends will demand proof that the other knows the authentication key.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If authentication is requested but no authentication key is specified then the return value of `current_process().authkey` is used (see `Process`).
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] This value will be automatically inherited by any `Process` object that the current process creates.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] This means that (by default) all processes of a multi-process program will share a single authentication key which can be used when setting up connections between themselves.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Suitable authentication keys can also be generated by using `os.urandom()`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] This authentication protects `Listener` and `Client()` connections, which are reachable by address.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] It is not applied to the anonymous pipes created by `Pipe()` or used internally by `Queue`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] `multiprocessing` treats all local processes running as the same user as trusted; on most operating systems such processes can access each other’s pipe file descriptors regardless.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Applications that require isolation between processes of the same user must arrange it at the operating-system level – for example, by running workers under a different user account or in a sandbox.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Note, however, that the `logging` package does not use process shared locks so it is possible (depending on the handler type) for messages from different processes to get mixed up.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Returns the logger used by `multiprocessing`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] If necessary, a new one will be created.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] When first created the logger has level `logging.NOTSET` and no default handler.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Messages sent to this logger will not by default propagate to the root logger.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Note that on Windows child processes will only inherit the level of the parent process’s logger – any other customization of the logger will not be inherited.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] This function performs a call to `get_logger()` but in addition to returning the logger created by get_logger, it adds a handler which sends output to `sys.stderr` using format `'[%(levelname)s/%(processName)s] %(message)s'`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] You can modify `levelname` of the logger by passing a `level` argument.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] For a full table of logging levels, see the `logging` module.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] `multiprocessing.dummy` replicates the API of `multiprocessing` but is no more than a wrapper around the `threading` module.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] In particular, the `Pool` function provided by `multiprocessing.dummy` returns an instance of `ThreadPool`, which is a subclass of `Pool` that supports all the same method calls but uses a pool of worker threads rather than worker processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A thread pool object which controls a pool of worker threads to which jobs can be submitted.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] `ThreadPool` instances are fully interface compatible with `Pool` instances, and their resources must also be properly managed, either by using the pool as a context manager or by calling `close()` and `terminate()` manually.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Unlike `Pool`, *maxtasksperchild* and *context* cannot be provided.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] A `ThreadPool` shares the same interface as `Pool`, which is designed around a pool of processes and predates the introduction of the `concurrent.futures` module.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] As such, it inherits some operations that don’t make sense for a pool backed by threads, and it has its own type for representing the status of asynchronous jobs, `AsyncResult`, that is not understood by any other libraries.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p03] Users should generally prefer to use `concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor`, which has a simpler interface that was designed around threads from the start, and which returns `concurrent.futures.Future` instances that are compatible with many other libraries, including `asyncio`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p04] There are certain guidelines and idioms which should be adhered to when using `multiprocessing`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p04] The following applies to all start methods.
[src:multiprocessing-python/multiprocessing-p04] There are a few extra restrictions which don’t apply to the *fork* start method.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] In computing, a **process** is the instance of a computer program that is being executed by one or many threads.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Depending on the OS, a process may be made up of multiple threads of execution that execute instructions concurrently.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] While a computer program is a passive collection of instructions typically stored in a file on disk, a process is the execution of those instructions after being loaded from the disk into memory.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Several processes may be associated with the same program; for example, opening up several instances of the same program often results in more than one process being executed.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Multitasking is a method to allow multiple processes to share processors (CPUs) and other system resources.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Each CPU (core) executes a single process at a time.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] However, multitasking allows each processor to switch between tasks that are being executed without having to wait for each task to finish (preemption).
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] A common form of multitasking is provided by CPU's time-sharing that is a method for interleaving the execution of users' processes and threads, and even of independent kernel tasks – although the latter feature is feasible only in preemptive kernels such as Linux.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Preemption has an important side effect for interactive processes that are given higher priority with respect to CPU-bound processes; therefore users are immediately assigned computing resources at the simple pressing of a key or when moving a mouse.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Furthermore, applications like video and music reproduction are given some kind of real-time priority, preempting any other lower priority process.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] In time-sharing systems, context switches are performed rapidly, which makes it seem like multiple processes are being executed simultaneously on the same processor.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] This seemingly-simultaneous execution of multiple processes is called concurrency.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] For security and reliability, most modern operating systems prevent direct communication between independent processes, providing strictly mediated and controlled inter-process communication.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] The operating system holds most of this information about active processes in data structures called process control blocks.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Any subset of the resources, typically at least the processor state, may be associated with each of the process' threads in operating systems that support threads or *child* processes.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] The operating system keeps its processes separate and allocates the resources they need, so that they are less likely to interfere with each other and cause system failures (e.g., deadlock or thrashing).
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] The operating system may also provide mechanisms for inter-process communication to enable processes to interact in safe and predictable ways.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] It is usual to associate a single process with a main program, and child processes with any spin-off, parallel processes, which behave like asynchronous subroutines.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] A process is said to *own* resources, of which an *image* of its program (in memory) is one such resource.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] However, in multiprocessing systems *many* processes may run off of, or share, the same reentrant program at the same location in memory, but each process is said to own its own *image* of the program.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Processes are often called "tasks" in embedded operating systems.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] The sense of "process" (or task) is "something that takes up time", as opposed to "memory", which is "something that takes up space".
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] The above description applies to both processes managed by an operating system, and processes as defined by process calculi.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] If a process requests something for which it must wait, it will be blocked.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] When the process is in the blocked state, it is eligible for swapping to disk, but this is transparent in a virtual memory system, where regions of a process's memory may be really on disk and not in main memory at any time.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Even portions of active processes/tasks (executing programs) are eligible for swapping to disk, if the portions have not been used recently.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Not all parts of an executing program and its data have to be in physical memory for the associated process to be active.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] An operating system kernel that allows multitasking needs processes to have certain states.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Names for these states are not standardised, but they have similar functionality.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] When processes need to communicate with each other they must share parts of their address spaces or use other forms of inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] For instance in a shell pipeline, the output of the first process needs to pass to the second one, and so on.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] By the early 1960s, computer control software had evolved from monitor control software, for example IBSYS, to executive control software.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Over time, computers got faster while computer time was still neither cheap nor fully utilized; such an environment made multiprogramming possible and necessary.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Multiprogramming means that several programs run concurrently.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] At first, more than one program ran on a single processor, as a result of underlying uniprocessor computer architecture, and they shared scarce and limited hardware resources; consequently, the concurrency was of a *serial* nature.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] On later systems with multiple processors, multiple programs may run concurrently in *parallel*.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Programs consist of sequences of instructions for processors.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] A single processor can run only one instruction at a time: it is impossible to run more programs at the same time.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] A program might need some resource, such as an input device, which has a large delay, or a program might start some slow operation, such as sending output to a printer.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] This would lead to processor being "idle" (unused).
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] To keep the processor busy at all times, the execution of such a program is halted and the operating system switches the processor to run another program.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] To the user, it will appear that the programs run at the same time (hence the term "parallel").
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] Shortly thereafter, the notion of a "program" was expanded to the notion of an "executing program and its context".
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] The concept of a process was born, which also became necessary with the invention of re-entrant code.
[src:multiprocessing-python/process-computing] However, with the advent of concepts such as time-sharing, computer networks, and multiple-CPU shared memory computers, the old "multiprogramming" gave way to true multitasking, multiprocessing and, later, multithreading.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] In computing, the **producer-consumer problem** (also known as the **bounded-buffer problem**) is a family of problems described by Edsger W.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] Dijkstra wrote about the unbounded buffer case: "We consider two processes, which are called the 'producer' and the 'consumer' respectively.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The producer is a cyclic process and each time it goes through its cycle it produces a certain portion of information, that has to be processed by the consumer.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The consumer is also a cyclic process and each time it goes through its cycle, it can process the next portion of information, as has been produced by the producer ...
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] He wrote about the bounded buffer case: "We have studied a producer and a consumer coupled via a buffer with unbounded capacity ...
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] And about the multiple producer-consumer case: "We consider a number of producer/consumer pairs, where pairi is coupled via an information stream containing ni portions.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] Per Brinch Hansen and Niklaus Wirth saw soon the problem of semaphores: "I have come to the same conclusion with regard to semaphores, namely that they are not suitable for higher level languages.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The original semaphore bounded buffer solution was written in ALGOL style.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The buffer can store N portions or elements.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The "number of queueing portions" semaphore counts the filled locations in the buffer, the "number of empty positions" semaphore counts the empty locations in the buffer and the semaphore "buffer manipulation" works as mutex for the buffer put and get operations.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] If the buffer is full, that is the number of empty positions is zero, the producer thread will wait in the P(number of empty positions) operation.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] If the buffer is empty, that is the number of queueing portions is zero, the consumer thread will wait in the P(number of queueing portions) operation.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The V() operations release the semaphores.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] As a side effect, a thread can move from the wait queue to the ready queue.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The P() operation decreases the semaphore value down to zero.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The V() operation increases the semaphore value.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] As of C++ 20, semaphores are part of the language.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] Dijkstra's solution can easily be written in modern C++.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The variable buffer_manipulation is a mutex.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The semaphore feature of acquiring in one thread and releasing in another thread is not needed.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The lock_guard() statement instead of a lock() and unlock() pair is C++ RAII.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The lock_guard destructor ensures lock release in case of an exception.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] This solution can handle multiple consumer threads and/or multiple producer threads.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] Per Brinch Hansen defined the monitor: I will use the term monitor to denote a shared variable and the set of meaningful operations on it.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The purpose of a monitor is to control the scheduling of resources among individual processes according to a certain policy.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] Tony Hoare laid a theoretical foundation for the monitor.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The monitor is an object that contains variables `buffer`, `head`, `tail` and `count` to realize a circular buffer, the condition variables `nonempty` and `nonfull` for synchronization and the methods `append` and `remove` to access the bounded buffer.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The monitor operation wait corresponds to the semaphore operation P or acquire, signal corresponds to V or release.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The circled operation (+) are taken modulo N.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The presented Pascal style pseudo code shows a Hoare monitor.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] A Mesa monitor uses `while count` instead of `if count`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The C++ version needs an additional mutex for technical reasons.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] It uses assert to enforce the preconditions for the buffer add and remove operations.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The very first producer-consumer solution in the Electrologica computers used 'channels'.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] Hoare defined channels: An alternative to explicit naming of source and destination would be to name a port through which communication is to take place.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The port names would be local to the processes, and the manner in which pairs of ports are to be connected by channels could be declared in the head of a parallel command.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] Brinch Hansen implemented channels in the programming languages Joyce and Super Pascal.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The Plan 9 operating system programming language Alef, the Inferno operating system programming language Limbo have channels.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The program entry point is at function `threadmain`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The function call `ch = chancreate(sizeof(ulong), 1)` creates the channel, the function call `sendul(ch, i)` sends a value into the channel and the function call `p = recvul(ch)` receives a value from the channel.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The programming language Go has channels, too.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The Go producer-consumer solution uses the main Go routine for consumer and creates a new, unnamed Go routine for the producer.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The two Go routines are connected with channel ch.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] This channel can queue up to three int values.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The statement `ch := make(chan int, 3)` creates the channel, the statement `ch <- produceMessage()` sends a value into the channel and the statement `recvMsg := range ch` receives a value from the channel.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The allocation of memory resources, the allocation of processing resources, and the synchronization of resources are done by the programming language automatically.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] Leslie Lamport documented a bounded buffer producer-consumer solution for one producer and one consumer: We assume that the buffer can hold at most b messages, b >= 1.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] In our solution, we let k be a constant greater than b, and let s and r be integer variables assuming values between 0 and k-1.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] We assume that initially s=r and the buffer is empty.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] By choosing k to be a multiple of b, the buffer can be implemented as an array B [0: b - 1].
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The producer simply puts each new message into B[s mod b], and the consumer takes each message from B[r mod b].
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The algorithm is shown below, generalized for infinite k.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The Lamport solution uses busy waiting in the thread instead of waiting in the scheduler.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] This solution neglects the impact of scheduler thread switch at inconvenient times.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] If the first thread has read a variable value from memory, the scheduler switches to the second thread that changes the variable value, and the scheduler switches back to the first thread then the first thread uses the old value of the variable, not the current value.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] Atomic read-modify-write solves this problem.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] Modern C++ offers `atomic` variables and operations for multi-thread programming.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The following busy waiting C++11 solution for one producer and one consumer uses atomic read-modify-write operations `fetch_add` and `fetch_sub` on the atomic variable `count`.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The circular buffer index variables `head` and `tail` are thread-local and therefore not relevant for memory consistency.
[src:multiprocessing-python/producer-consumer-problem] The variable `count` controls the busy waiting of the producer and consumer thread.
